00:39:41.160 --> 00:39:44.400
Because if you measure in
either of three directions,

00:39:44.400 --> 00:39:47.120
they have to have
an answer for that.

00:39:47.120 --> 00:39:49.650
So here's a label
for a particle.

00:39:55.688 --> 00:40:02.240
And for example,
a-plus, b-minus, c-plus.

00:40:02.240 --> 00:40:07.100
So if you measure, it would
give spin in a direction

00:40:07.100 --> 00:40:09.440
plus h bar over 2.

00:40:09.440 --> 00:40:14.530
Spin in the b direction minus--
well, in the b direction

00:40:14.530 --> 00:40:17.190
would give you
minus h bar over 2.

00:40:17.190 --> 00:40:22.880
Spin in the c direction would
give you plus h bar over 2 .

00:40:25.850 --> 00:40:28.710
So we're not measuring
simultaneously.

00:40:28.710 --> 00:40:31.690
We're just asking, well,
you take a particle,

00:40:31.690 --> 00:40:33.850
do a measurement,
and see what you get.

00:40:37.200 --> 00:40:40.440
And we're always going to
be asking for probabilities

00:40:40.440 --> 00:40:44.380
of this kind, probably that the
first particle is doing this

00:40:44.380 --> 00:40:47.980
and the second is doing that.

00:40:47.980 --> 00:40:53.080
Well, EPR would start
now with particles

00:40:53.080 --> 00:40:58.403
again, particle 1, particle 2.

00:41:01.820 --> 00:41:03.120
And populations.

00:41:03.120 --> 00:41:05.400
So let's list quickly
the particles.

00:41:05.400 --> 00:41:09.040
a-plus, b-plus, c-plus.

00:41:09.040 --> 00:41:15.970
Then you will go
a-plus, b-plus, c-minus.

00:41:15.970 --> 00:41:18.540
Then you've done the
c-plus, c-minus here.

00:41:18.540 --> 00:41:20.770
You go for two more.

00:41:20.770 --> 00:41:25.900
A-plus, b-minus, c-plus.

00:41:25.900 --> 00:41:28.750
a-plus, b-minus, c-minus.

00:41:33.440 --> 00:41:37.450
I was supposed to
fit four more there.

00:41:37.450 --> 00:41:38.240
Can I?

00:41:38.240 --> 00:41:41.210
Well, I will try. a-minus.

00:41:41.210 --> 00:41:43.306
Now you've done all
the four a-pluses

00:41:43.306 --> 00:41:44.430
so you need four a-minuses.

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:57.810
Then you have b-plus, b-plus,
b-minus, b-minus, c-plus,

00:41:57.810 --> 00:42:01.100
c-minus, c-plus, c-minus.

00:42:01.100 --> 00:42:02.545
I got all, I think.

00:42:05.350 --> 00:42:08.480
And particle two of
course is correlated.

00:42:08.480 --> 00:42:10.800
You would say, well, I
don't need to write it.

00:42:10.800 --> 00:42:15.800
But it helps seeing what's going
on so I'll write it. a-minus,

00:42:15.800 --> 00:42:21.980
b-minus, c-minus,
a-minus, b-minus,

00:42:21.980 --> 00:42:29.810
c-plus, a-minus-- let's use
bars here-- a-minus, b-plus,

00:42:29.810 --> 00:42:38.410
c-minus, a-minus, b-plus,
c-plus, a-plus, b-minus,

00:42:38.410 --> 00:42:47.430
c-minus, a-plus, b-minus,
c-plus, a-plus, b-plus,

00:42:47.430 --> 00:42:54.730
c-minus, a-plus, b-minus,
c-- this one is minus

00:42:54.730 --> 00:42:56.750
so it's plus here.

00:42:56.750 --> 00:42:58.080
We're done.

00:42:58.080 --> 00:43:01.560
Lots of labels.

00:43:01.560 --> 00:43:03.860
And you could say,
well, maybe you

00:43:03.860 --> 00:43:06.710
want to put 1/8 in each of them.

00:43:06.710 --> 00:43:09.290
But actually the argument
is more interesting.

00:43:09.290 --> 00:43:13.700
It doesn't need you have
to try to put fractions.

00:43:13.700 --> 00:43:18.020
So let's consider that there's
a total number of particles

00:43:18.020 --> 00:43:24.030
N, which is N1 plus up to N8.

00:43:24.030 --> 00:43:29.370
And here are N1 of this,
N2 of this, N3 of this,

00:43:29.370 --> 00:43:35.670
N4 of this, N5, N6, N7, and N8.

00:43:44.630 --> 00:43:46.444
Let's see how--

00:43:49.860 --> 00:43:51.640
All right, so we have that.

00:43:55.050 --> 00:43:57.700
Well, it takes
imagination to see

00:43:57.700 --> 00:44:03.370
how you're going to run
into some contradiction.

00:44:03.370 --> 00:44:05.930
So what is the basis
for the contradiction?

00:44:05.930 --> 00:44:12.840
Somehow this formula, which
is really quantum mechanical

00:44:12.840 --> 00:44:17.820
must eventually go wrong
with all these attempts

00:44:17.820 --> 00:44:21.090
to deny that the world
is quantum mechanical.

00:44:21.090 --> 00:44:27.870
So we could split again those
particles into equal fractions.

00:44:27.870 --> 00:44:29.710
But there's no need to do that.

00:44:29.710 --> 00:44:31.950
And it's clearer if you don't.

00:44:31.950 --> 00:44:36.710
So you try to combine the three
directions into one equation.

00:44:36.710 --> 00:44:40.150
So one way to do that
would be to say, OK,

00:44:40.150 --> 00:44:44.830
what is the probability that
you get a-plus and b-plus?

00:44:44.830 --> 00:44:47.700
So this is for the
particle number 1.

00:44:47.700 --> 00:44:50.180
And this is particle number 2.

00:44:50.180 --> 00:44:53.810
So then you must
look at the table

00:44:53.810 --> 00:44:56.000
and say which one's do that.

00:44:56.000 --> 00:44:57.930
Well, you need
a-plus in the first

00:44:57.930 --> 00:45:00.720
so it's one of the
first four rows.

00:45:00.720 --> 00:45:02.770
And b-plus in the second.

00:45:02.770 --> 00:45:16.600
So actually, it's these two
cases, N3 and N4, over N.

00:45:16.600 --> 00:45:18.970
We want to involve
three directions.

00:45:18.970 --> 00:45:21.660
So let's go for another one.

00:45:21.660 --> 00:45:27.180
P of a-plus with c-plus.

00:45:27.180 --> 00:45:28.900
Let's see how much is that.

00:45:28.900 --> 00:45:31.320
Again, this is for
the first particle.

00:45:31.320 --> 00:45:34.500
This is for the second particle.

00:45:34.500 --> 00:45:39.310
So I must look at
the first four rows.

00:45:39.310 --> 00:45:43.380
And see that you have an a-plus.

00:45:43.380 --> 00:45:46.530
First part is in a-plus
for the first four rows.

00:45:46.530 --> 00:45:48.590
But the second
should be in c-plus

00:45:48.590 --> 00:45:52.860
and that is cases N2 and N4.

00:45:52.860 --> 00:46:00.950
So we get N2 plus
N4 here over N.

00:46:00.950 --> 00:46:06.276
Well, we've involved
this a with b, a with c.

00:46:06.276 --> 00:46:10.880
How about involving b with c?

00:46:10.880 --> 00:46:13.835
So I'll put c-plus,
b-plus, for example.

00:46:18.190 --> 00:46:22.310
OK c-plus, b-plus.

00:46:22.310 --> 00:46:26.260
I must look at c-pluses,
and b-pluses, no.

00:46:26.260 --> 00:46:27.950
C-plus and b-plus, yes.

00:46:27.950 --> 00:46:31.840
N3 is there, which is good
because it already was there.

00:46:34.690 --> 00:46:36.510
And which else?

00:46:36.510 --> 00:46:39.620
c-plus and b-plus.

00:46:39.620 --> 00:46:41.240
c-plus, no.

00:46:41.240 --> 00:46:42.851
c-plus here b-plus, yes.

00:46:42.851 --> 00:46:43.350
N7.

00:46:53.820 --> 00:47:15.870
Now N3 plus N4 is less than
N3 plus N7 plus N4 plus N2.

00:47:15.870 --> 00:47:19.060
You see you have N3 and N4.

00:47:19.060 --> 00:47:24.410
And now I add whatever
N7 and N2 are.

00:47:24.410 --> 00:47:29.110
And that's then an
inequality because it's

00:47:29.110 --> 00:47:31.130
going to be more cases.

00:47:31.130 --> 00:47:40.780
Now I divide by N. So
you obtain an inequality

00:47:40.780 --> 00:47:49.630
that P of a-plus,
b-plus is less than

00:47:49.630 --> 00:47:56.550
or equal than N3 plus
N7 and N4 plus N2.

00:47:56.550 --> 00:48:03.770
I'll right the second
first, P of a-plus, c-plus

00:48:03.770 --> 00:48:07.600
plus P of c-plus, b-plus.

00:48:15.190 --> 00:48:19.700
So I didn't put specific
populations 1/3, 1/4.

00:48:19.700 --> 00:48:25.360
But in general whatever
populations you choose,

00:48:25.360 --> 00:48:28.450
this inequality must hold.

00:48:28.450 --> 00:48:31.040
So that's the more
clever strategy.

00:48:31.040 --> 00:48:34.730
Because suppose you
choose some populations

00:48:34.730 --> 00:48:37.580
and you don't get
in trouble, well,

00:48:37.580 --> 00:48:39.230
maybe with some
other populations

00:48:39.230 --> 00:48:40.480
you would get in trouble.

00:48:40.480 --> 00:48:43.380
Maybe it's not so easy to
get the relative factors.

00:48:43.380 --> 00:48:47.210
So here is something
that must be

00:48:47.210 --> 00:48:50.810
true whatever
populations you choose.

00:48:50.810 --> 00:48:56.030
And now that is
Bell's inequality.

00:48:56.030 --> 00:49:02.190
So the achievement
of Bell is to somehow

00:49:02.190 --> 00:49:08.960
translate this assumption of
realism into an inequality.

00:49:08.960 --> 00:49:17.180
And now quantum mechanics has
a formula for these things,

00:49:17.180 --> 00:49:18.450
for this probability.

00:49:18.450 --> 00:49:22.260
So we can test
whether this is true.

00:49:22.260 --> 00:49:25.030
So let's do that.

00:49:25.030 --> 00:49:28.200
This is the so-called
Bell inequality.

00:49:28.200 --> 00:49:34.605
So if quantum mechanics is
true, the following should hold.

00:49:42.630 --> 00:49:43.865
Let's see that.

00:49:48.590 --> 00:50:02.340
If QM is true,
well, there should

00:50:02.340 --> 00:50:04.600
be a problem with
this inequality.

00:50:04.600 --> 00:50:07.280
So let's see what happens.

00:50:07.280 --> 00:50:09.490
Let's see if it's
true, this inequality.

00:50:13.900 --> 00:50:16.050
Is it really true?

00:50:16.050 --> 00:50:19.980
Well, the left
hand side would be,

00:50:19.980 --> 00:50:23.760
given the formula
that we had, 1/2

00:50:23.760 --> 00:50:29.250
of the sine squared
of theta ab over 2.

00:50:33.750 --> 00:50:37.540
So let me just
emphasize, this was

00:50:37.540 --> 00:50:40.085
derived using local realism.

00:50:44.190 --> 00:50:46.790
Local realism gives that.

00:50:46.790 --> 00:50:50.910
So you do the experiment,
get these probabilities.

00:50:50.910 --> 00:50:55.350
And if realism is
true, this should hold.

00:50:55.350 --> 00:50:58.270
Let's see what quantum
mechanics has to say.

00:50:58.270 --> 00:51:03.390
Let's plug-in the values that
you get from quantum mechanics.

00:51:03.390 --> 00:51:05.500
Now we calculated
this probability.

00:51:05.500 --> 00:51:06.850
We put the first term.

00:51:06.850 --> 00:51:12.950
Here is sine squared of
theta ac over 2 and 1/2

00:51:12.950 --> 00:51:17.130
of sine squared theta bc over 2.

00:51:21.600 --> 00:51:23.810
So does that work?

00:51:23.810 --> 00:51:25.290
Does that always work?

00:51:25.290 --> 00:51:31.310
Can I orient this axis in
such a way to disprove EPR?

00:51:31.310 --> 00:51:36.150
And in fact, it turns out
to be quite easy to do that.

00:51:36.150 --> 00:51:41.280
So you choose three
vectors like this.

00:51:41.280 --> 00:51:50.610
ac, bc, so c here, a here,
and b here, I believe.

00:51:50.610 --> 00:51:52.000
Yep.

00:51:52.000 --> 00:51:55.770
So put an angle theta here.

00:51:55.770 --> 00:51:58.550
An angle theta here.

00:51:58.550 --> 00:52:00.650
And then what do you have?

00:52:00.650 --> 00:52:05.970
Theta ab would be 2 theta.

00:52:05.970 --> 00:52:15.210
Theta ac would be equal to
theta bc equal to theta.

00:52:15.210 --> 00:52:20.300
That's a pretty nice
simple choice of angles.

00:52:20.300 --> 00:52:23.260
If you choose these
angles now, let's

00:52:23.260 --> 00:52:26.060
see what happens
with our inequality.

00:52:26.060 --> 00:52:33.250
So you get 1/2 sine squared
theta ab over 2 would be theta.

00:52:33.250 --> 00:52:37.140
Is it less than
or equal to this?

00:52:37.140 --> 00:52:39.120
Well, these two become the same.

00:52:39.120 --> 00:52:44.090
So you get sine squared
of theta over 2.

00:52:48.080 --> 00:52:50.680
Violated or not violated?

00:52:50.680 --> 00:52:55.530
Is it true or false,
this, for all theta?

00:52:55.530 --> 00:52:56.330
What do you say?

00:53:02.150 --> 00:53:04.094
Yes?

00:53:04.094 --> 00:53:09.670
STUDENT: If theta is less
than pi, that's not true.

00:53:09.670 --> 00:53:11.770
PROFESSOR: Close.

00:53:11.770 --> 00:53:14.440
It's not true for a small theta.

00:53:14.440 --> 00:53:19.640
So if you're this, and
you're desperate to know,

00:53:19.640 --> 00:53:21.290
the thing you have
to do is assume

00:53:21.290 --> 00:53:23.030
theta is very, very small.

00:53:23.030 --> 00:53:24.530
See if you get in trouble.

00:53:24.530 --> 00:53:25.920
How much is this?

00:53:25.920 --> 00:53:27.843
1/2 theta squared.

00:53:31.715 --> 00:53:33.531
Let's see.

00:53:33.531 --> 00:53:34.900
Half of this one?

00:53:34.900 --> 00:53:36.280
Yeah.

00:53:36.280 --> 00:53:37.595
And how much is this?

00:53:37.595 --> 00:53:40.063
This is theta squared over 4.

00:53:40.063 --> 00:53:43.010
Sorry, I was not seeing it.

00:53:43.010 --> 00:53:46.780
Sine theta for small
theta is roughly theta.

00:53:46.780 --> 00:53:49.060
So here is theta over 2 squared.

00:53:49.060 --> 00:53:51.820
But here is 1/2 theta squared.

00:53:51.820 --> 00:53:54.590
And it's false.

00:53:54.590 --> 00:53:57.280
The 1/2 theta squared
is not smaller

00:53:57.280 --> 00:53:59.800
than one quarter theta squared.

00:53:59.800 --> 00:54:04.260
And in fact, for
theta equal pi over 2,

00:54:04.260 --> 00:54:07.640
I think this is an equality.

00:54:07.640 --> 00:54:11.260
Because theta equal
pi over 2, you

00:54:11.260 --> 00:54:14.210
get on the left hand
side 1/2 less than

00:54:14.210 --> 00:54:22.030
or equal than sine of 45
degrees, which is correct.

00:54:22.030 --> 00:54:25.430
So it's an equality
of pi over 2.

00:54:25.430 --> 00:54:27.770
Fails below.

00:54:27.770 --> 00:54:31.760
So it was a shock.

00:54:31.760 --> 00:54:37.370
That if you could do an
experiment in quantum mechanics

00:54:37.370 --> 00:54:45.290
and experiment with correlated,
entangled particles,

00:54:45.290 --> 00:54:48.580
that you could to measure
these probabilities,

00:54:48.580 --> 00:54:50.060
these correlations.

00:54:50.060 --> 00:54:54.740
And you would obtain a result
that actually contradicts

00:54:54.740 --> 00:54:57.710
for certain alignments
of your experiments

00:54:57.710 --> 00:55:00.440
the assumptions
of local realism.

00:55:00.440 --> 00:55:05.360
So it was a great
result of Bell to show

00:55:05.360 --> 00:55:09.630
that quantum mechanics
is in contradiction

00:55:09.630 --> 00:55:12.230
with local realism.

00:55:12.230 --> 00:55:18.600
There's no way to keep the
ideas of quantum mechanics

00:55:18.600 --> 00:55:21.550
and put hidden
variables and assume

00:55:21.550 --> 00:55:24.120
that there's real
values for things

00:55:24.120 --> 00:55:27.190
and that there's no
effect at a distance.

00:55:27.190 --> 00:55:30.330
It would all be contradicted
by an experiment.

00:55:30.330 --> 00:55:34.620
That was done later and
the definite version

00:55:34.620 --> 00:55:39.200
of the experiments
around 1980 or '82

00:55:39.200 --> 00:55:42.000
by Alan Aspect and others.

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:46.300
Very clever experiments worth
reading and understanding.

00:55:46.300 --> 00:55:51.780
But confirmed that the
quantum mechanical result

00:55:51.780 --> 00:55:54.730
is really true by
measuring correlated pairs.

00:55:54.730 --> 00:55:57.493
And this inequality is violated.

00:55:57.493 --> 00:55:57.993
Yes?

00:55:57.993 --> 00:56:00.132
STUDENT: So what about
David Bohm's theory

00:56:00.132 --> 00:56:01.746
of hidden variables
quantum mechanics?

00:56:01.746 --> 00:56:02.245
So--

00:56:02.245 --> 00:56:05.000
PROFESSOR: David
Bohm's theory of what?

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:07.820
STUDENT: His hidden variable
quantum mechanics theory

00:56:07.820 --> 00:56:10.594
allegedly reproduces the same
results as quantum mechanics

00:56:10.594 --> 00:56:13.024
but it's still a hidden
variables theory.

00:56:13.024 --> 00:56:16.140
PROFESSOR: I don't think there's
