01:01:15.910 --> 01:01:19.210
through the things that
happen there so that you

01:01:19.210 --> 01:01:21.770
get a view of what
we're going to do.

01:01:21.770 --> 01:01:28.210
We're going to work with this
thing in a elegant way using

01:01:28.210 --> 01:01:30.640
vector notation for
operators is going

01:01:30.640 --> 01:01:33.560
to help us understand
things better.

01:01:33.560 --> 01:01:38.050
So we've seen angular
momentum before.

01:01:38.050 --> 01:01:43.250
And let me summarize simple
things that we know about it.

01:01:43.250 --> 01:01:49.390
If you have angular momentum,
and let's begin with orbital.

01:01:49.390 --> 01:01:56.950
This is what we have when we
take Lx to be y Pz minus z Py.

01:01:59.960 --> 01:02:04.768
Ly equals z Px minus x Pz.

01:02:08.330 --> 01:02:14.432
And Lz to be equal
to x Py minus y Pz.

01:02:18.010 --> 01:02:22.240
These are the angular momentum,
orbital angular momentum

01:02:22.240 --> 01:02:24.760
operators.

01:02:24.760 --> 01:02:28.270
Now, it's better for
many things to use labels

01:02:28.270 --> 01:02:32.900
like x, y, and z,
those operators.

01:02:32.900 --> 01:02:36.460
Call them x1 hat,
x2 hat, x3 hat.

01:02:40.360 --> 01:02:50.165
And Px, Py, Pz, P1, P2, P3.

01:02:53.220 --> 01:02:57.740
In that way you can write
commutation relations like xi,

01:02:57.740 --> 01:03:04.160
Pj equal i h bar delta ij.

01:03:04.160 --> 01:03:13.180
xi with xj equal
pi with pj equal 0.

01:03:13.180 --> 01:03:16.640
So it allows you to write
things more quickly.

01:03:19.570 --> 01:03:22.110
In fact, the angular
momentum operators

01:03:22.110 --> 01:03:24.490
become also a little simpler.

01:03:24.490 --> 01:03:33.360
It's sort of x2 P3 minus x3 P2.

01:03:33.360 --> 01:03:38.900
And you'll have the x,
y, z labels and all that.

01:03:38.900 --> 01:03:43.920
So we want to use
vector notation.

01:03:43.920 --> 01:03:46.820
Now, vector notation, you
can do it in two ways.

01:03:46.820 --> 01:03:48.220
You can talk about triplets.

01:03:48.220 --> 01:03:51.670
Those are vectors.

01:03:51.670 --> 01:03:55.440
Or you can form the
vectors themselves.

01:03:55.440 --> 01:03:57.270
Now if you form the
vectors, you get

01:03:57.270 --> 01:04:00.320
objects that sometimes are
a little disconcerting.

01:04:00.320 --> 01:04:03.480
But we try that they not be so.

01:04:03.480 --> 01:04:10.970
So here is the r
vector operator.

01:04:10.970 --> 01:04:14.250
You could think of it as
the triplet of x, y, and z.

01:04:14.250 --> 01:04:19.700
But let's call it like this,
x thing times the first basis

01:04:19.700 --> 01:04:25.510
vector plus y operator times
the second basis vector

01:04:25.510 --> 01:04:29.470
plus z operator times
the third basis vector.

01:04:29.470 --> 01:04:32.050
And we've done things like that.

01:04:32.050 --> 01:04:35.490
And we understand that
these basis vectors really

01:04:35.490 --> 01:04:38.910
don't talk with these operators.

01:04:38.910 --> 01:04:40.820
They can be moved
across each other.

01:04:40.820 --> 01:04:43.980
The basis vectors
are things that

01:04:43.980 --> 01:04:47.455
help you write
expressions, rather,

01:04:47.455 --> 01:04:50.430
at talking about triplets.

01:04:50.430 --> 01:04:51.765
Same thing for momentum.

01:04:55.030 --> 01:04:56.200
Let's do it this way.

01:04:56.200 --> 01:05:05.370
P1 e1 plus P2 e2 plus P3 e3.

01:05:05.370 --> 01:05:10.420
And finally, well, angular
momentum, the vector operator--

01:05:10.420 --> 01:05:14.930
you've done a lot of the
angular momentum vector operator

01:05:14.930 --> 01:05:16.810
for spin.

01:05:16.810 --> 01:05:30.590
So here you would put Lx or
L1 e1 plus L2 e2 plus L3 e3.

01:05:30.590 --> 01:05:37.510
So those are ways
to write equations

01:05:37.510 --> 01:05:42.850
that carry all the operators
and treat them as vectors, even

01:05:42.850 --> 01:05:44.200
though they're operators.

01:05:44.200 --> 01:05:46.460
So they're unusual vectors.

01:05:46.460 --> 01:05:52.690
They're vectors whose components
are operators, are not numbers.

01:05:52.690 --> 01:06:00.520
So the obvious question
is, what changes then?

01:06:00.520 --> 01:06:03.520
So we're going to define
dot product and cross

01:06:03.520 --> 01:06:06.770
products as we had before.

01:06:06.770 --> 01:06:12.380
But we have to be a little aware
that when we write these things

01:06:12.380 --> 01:06:15.360
we could make a mistake
unless we're not careful.

01:06:15.360 --> 01:06:18.560
So here are two
vector operators.

01:06:25.590 --> 01:06:29.990
What is the dot product of
these two vector operators?

01:06:29.990 --> 01:06:34.870
Well, you know it's supposed to
be the first component of this

01:06:34.870 --> 01:06:37.850
and the first component of that,
second second, third third.

01:06:37.850 --> 01:06:45.970
So it should be ai bi, summed.

01:06:45.970 --> 01:06:49.050
Repeated in this is
our [? summed. ?]

01:06:49.050 --> 01:06:55.110
Now, I should not write
bi ai with a reverse order

01:06:55.110 --> 01:06:59.430
because this thing, the
components, are now operators.

01:06:59.430 --> 01:07:01.840
And maybe they don't commute.

01:07:01.840 --> 01:07:06.573
So I've defined this once
and for all to be this.

01:07:06.573 --> 01:07:14.490
And a cross b, the i-th
component of this thing

01:07:14.490 --> 01:07:18.040
is going to be defined
once and for all

01:07:18.040 --> 01:07:24.454
to be epsilon ijk aj bk.

01:07:28.250 --> 01:07:29.675
Definition.

01:07:29.675 --> 01:07:32.046
The a to the left of the b.

01:07:35.238 --> 01:07:42.770
And with this, we can
check our usual rules

01:07:42.770 --> 01:07:44.730
of manipulation of operators.

01:07:44.730 --> 01:07:46.270
So one more definition.

01:07:46.270 --> 01:07:53.790
a squared is going to be aa,
and it's going to be ai ai.

01:08:00.190 --> 01:08:09.050
Simplest calculation is a
dot b equals to b dot a.

01:08:13.910 --> 01:08:15.100
Yes or not?

01:08:15.100 --> 01:08:16.710
No, they're operators.

01:08:16.710 --> 01:08:18.950
So let's calculate
the difference.

01:08:18.950 --> 01:08:22.822
Let's get a little practice
calculating differences.

01:08:29.750 --> 01:08:38.840
So I write a dot b is
equal to ai bi, its sum.

01:08:38.840 --> 01:08:47.149
So then I say, that's
ai bi plus bi ai.

01:08:47.149 --> 01:08:52.400
You see the commutator
is ai bi minus bi ai.

01:08:52.400 --> 01:08:55.399
And I add it back.

01:08:55.399 --> 01:09:01.149
But this thing,
bi ai is b dot a.

01:09:01.149 --> 01:09:03.319
So here I've got a formula.

01:09:03.319 --> 01:09:12.910
a dot b is equal, actually, to
b dot a plus this commutator,

01:09:12.910 --> 01:09:16.220
ai bi.

01:09:16.220 --> 01:09:23.420
And now you've got a new formula
for operator vector analysis.

01:09:23.420 --> 01:09:26.090
a dot b and b dot
a are not the same

01:09:26.090 --> 01:09:28.850
but they differ by this thing.

01:09:28.850 --> 01:09:35.540
And a very important corollary,
very famous corollary,

01:09:35.540 --> 01:09:39.800
what is r dot p?

01:09:39.800 --> 01:09:43.410
Is it the same as p dot r?

01:09:43.410 --> 01:09:45.649
If you're working
quantum mechanics

01:09:45.649 --> 01:09:48.970
you maybe tempted to, oh r dot
p and p dot r are the same,

01:09:48.970 --> 01:09:52.489
but r and p don't commute,
so what is the difference?

01:09:52.489 --> 01:10:01.095
R dot p is equal to
p dot r plus xi pi.

01:10:05.250 --> 01:10:07.910
And how much is that?

01:10:07.910 --> 01:10:09.670
[INAUDIBLE]

01:10:09.670 --> 01:10:11.145
Sorry?

01:10:11.145 --> 01:10:12.260
STUDENT: i h bar.

01:10:12.260 --> 01:10:13.400
PROFESSOR: i h bar?

01:10:13.400 --> 01:10:14.080
STUDENT: 3.

01:10:14.080 --> 01:10:15.720
PROFESSOR: 3 i h bar.

01:10:15.720 --> 01:10:17.910
Yes, don't forget the sum.

01:10:17.910 --> 01:10:19.620
This is supposed to be summed.

01:10:19.620 --> 01:10:24.920
So it says x1 commutative,
p1, x2 going to 3 i h bar.

01:10:24.920 --> 01:10:28.010
So here's a famous formula.

01:10:28.010 --> 01:10:37.758
rp differs from pr plus three h
bar i-- i h bar, people write.

01:10:37.758 --> 01:10:38.650
i h bar.

01:10:43.840 --> 01:10:51.350
Another formula that you
would be curious to know.

01:10:51.350 --> 01:10:55.500
Well, the dot product was
supposed to be symmetric.

01:10:55.500 --> 01:10:57.240
It's not.

01:10:57.240 --> 01:11:03.230
The cross product is
supposed to be antisymmetric.

01:11:03.230 --> 01:11:04.750
Is it or not?

01:11:04.750 --> 01:11:14.244
a cross b sub i is equal
to epsilon ijk aj bk.

01:11:16.980 --> 01:11:18.530
What do I do next?

01:11:18.530 --> 01:11:21.780
I want to move the
a and b's around.

01:11:21.780 --> 01:11:26.970
So I'm going to replace
this by a commutator

01:11:26.970 --> 01:11:30.550
plus the other ordering, ijk.

01:11:30.550 --> 01:11:36.130
And I put here-- well, this
would be a parentheses-- aj bk

01:11:36.130 --> 01:11:40.860
commutator plus bk aj.

01:11:47.300 --> 01:11:52.290
Now, what do we get?

01:11:52.290 --> 01:11:55.870
Well, you have to look
at the second term.

01:11:55.870 --> 01:12:01.060
Let's put the first term here
because that's-- pretty much,

01:12:01.060 --> 01:12:04.370
we're not going to be
able to do much with it.

01:12:04.370 --> 01:12:05.564
aj bk.

01:12:08.640 --> 01:12:11.400
And the first term, I
would write it like this.

01:12:11.400 --> 01:12:24.510
Minus epsilon, flip
these two, ikj bk aj.

01:12:24.510 --> 01:12:28.360
If you do it like
that, then it sort of

01:12:28.360 --> 01:12:32.100
fits nicely with the definition
of the cross product.

01:12:32.100 --> 01:12:37.320
Because in the cross product,
the first label those here,

01:12:37.320 --> 01:12:41.490
the second label goes with the
last labeled of the epsilon.

01:12:41.490 --> 01:12:50.400
So this thing is
minus b cross a.

01:12:50.400 --> 01:12:52.270
And that was a cross b.

01:12:55.460 --> 01:13:01.690
Plus epsilon ijk aj bk.

01:13:07.330 --> 01:13:11.520
So that's your formula for
of how the cross product.

01:13:11.520 --> 01:13:13.860
Now fails to be antisymmetric.

01:13:16.700 --> 01:13:19.770
It's not necessarily
antisymmetric

01:13:19.770 --> 01:13:23.460
unless you're lucky.

01:13:23.460 --> 01:13:33.700
So here is a property that
you should try to think about.

01:13:33.700 --> 01:13:36.950
How about r cross r?

01:13:40.040 --> 01:13:44.095
Is it 0 or not 0?

01:13:44.095 --> 01:13:45.770
r cross r.

01:13:45.770 --> 01:13:49.970
You could say,
what can I do here?

01:13:49.970 --> 01:13:57.720
Well, r cross r
minus r cross r--

01:13:57.720 --> 01:14:00.440
two r across r's should
be equal to this.

01:14:00.440 --> 01:14:03.740
But both components are x's.

01:14:03.740 --> 01:14:06.355
So r cross r is 0.

01:14:09.230 --> 01:14:20.060
p cross p, that's also 0.

01:14:20.060 --> 01:14:25.145
And therefore, say,
L cross L, is it 0?

01:14:28.840 --> 01:14:29.340
Maybe.

01:14:29.340 --> 01:14:29.946
Is that right?

01:14:32.780 --> 01:14:34.492
No.

01:14:34.492 --> 01:14:38.790
L cross L, we'll see
it a little later,

01:14:38.790 --> 01:14:44.070
but it's not 0 because one L
with another L don't commute.

01:14:47.740 --> 01:14:52.250
Lights, high.

01:14:52.250 --> 01:14:52.830
OK.

01:14:52.830 --> 01:14:58.330
So L cross L is actually not
0 because this thing is not 0.

01:14:58.330 --> 01:15:03.010
We'll talk about
it a little later.

01:15:03.010 --> 01:15:06.480
But actually this is
a very famous one.

01:15:06.480 --> 01:15:11.050
L cross L is proportional
to L with an h bar.

01:15:11.050 --> 01:15:14.660
It's a lovely formula.

01:15:14.660 --> 01:15:18.080
So another interesting thing.

01:15:18.080 --> 01:15:25.520
Well, what is r cross p?

01:15:25.520 --> 01:15:34.380
r cross p, from this formula
we would minus p cross r.

01:15:34.380 --> 01:15:36.120
And how about the other term?

01:15:36.120 --> 01:15:37.860
Is it 0 or not 0?

01:15:37.860 --> 01:15:42.380
Is r cross p equal to minus
p cross r, or does that fail?

01:15:46.200 --> 01:15:47.816
Well, r and p don't commute.

01:15:50.390 --> 01:15:53.570
Actually this formula--
I should have-- somebody

01:15:53.570 --> 01:15:55.050
should have complained.

01:15:55.050 --> 01:15:58.690
This should be the i-th
component, the i-th component,

01:15:58.690 --> 01:16:00.050
and here is the i-th component.

01:16:04.210 --> 01:16:08.120
So i-th component
the i-th component.

01:16:08.120 --> 01:16:09.990
But then let's look at here.

01:16:09.990 --> 01:16:19.580
Epsilon ijk xj pk.

01:16:19.580 --> 01:16:26.670
But xj and pk is
i h bar delta jk.

01:16:26.670 --> 01:16:30.060
Now, this delta jk is symmetric.

01:16:30.060 --> 01:16:31.110
This is antisymmetric.

01:16:34.260 --> 01:16:40.760
You should get accustomed
to the idea that that is 0.

01:16:40.760 --> 01:16:44.730
If this is antisymmetric and
this is symmetric, this is 0.

01:16:44.730 --> 01:16:47.770
Let me do it one more time.

01:16:47.770 --> 01:16:50.620
Maybe this is not
completely obvious.

01:16:50.620 --> 01:16:56.460
But epsilon ijk delta jk.

01:16:56.460 --> 01:16:58.810
The intuition is also obvious.

01:16:58.810 --> 01:17:01.470
Epsilon must have the
three numbers different

01:17:01.470 --> 01:17:03.659
and this forces
them to be the same.

01:17:03.659 --> 01:17:04.575
But it's more general.

01:17:04.575 --> 01:17:07.740
If this is antisymmetric
and this is symmetric,

01:17:07.740 --> 01:17:09.200
they should be 0.

01:17:09.200 --> 01:17:16.560
And the way you do that is
you say relabel j and k.

01:17:16.560 --> 01:17:19.210
Whatever was called j call it k.

01:17:19.210 --> 01:17:21.790
Whatever was called k call it j.

01:17:21.790 --> 01:17:28.850
So this is epsilon ikj delta kj.

01:17:28.850 --> 01:17:31.900
And then we use the
symmetry properties.

01:17:31.900 --> 01:17:35.240
So when you exchange this
back you get a minus sign when

01:17:35.240 --> 01:17:37.360
you exchange this back
you don't get a sign.

01:17:37.360 --> 01:17:42.690
So minus ijk delta jk.

01:17:42.690 --> 01:17:47.480
So you have shown that this
thing is equal to minus itself.

01:17:47.480 --> 01:17:50.440
And therefore it's 0.

01:17:50.440 --> 01:17:52.790
Something that's equal
to minus itself is 0.

01:17:52.790 --> 01:17:55.400
So this is 0.

01:17:55.400 --> 01:18:02.910
And you've got that r cross
p is really minus p cross r.

01:18:02.910 --> 01:18:07.480
And that's what we call the
angular momentum, r cross p.

01:18:07.480 --> 01:18:11.320
But now you know that it's
also equal to minus p cross r.

01:18:18.490 --> 01:18:22.840
Let's see, one other
one, for example,

01:18:22.840 --> 01:18:24.520
that is classically true.

01:18:24.520 --> 01:18:27.450
Let's see if it's quantum
mechanically true.

01:18:32.430 --> 01:18:38.430
r dot L. The angular
momentum L is supposed

01:18:38.430 --> 01:18:41.980
to be perpendicular
to r and perpendicular

01:18:41.980 --> 01:18:44.290
to p because this is
the cross product.

01:18:44.290 --> 01:18:50.440
Is that true quantum
mechanically or not true?

01:18:50.440 --> 01:18:56.550
Well, maybe I didn't say--
well, we said L is r cross p.

01:18:56.550 --> 01:19:02.580
So this is r dot r cross p.

01:19:06.510 --> 01:19:17.942
So this would be ri times
epsilon ijk-- no, x-- xj pk.

01:19:21.790 --> 01:19:24.250
So what is this?

01:19:24.250 --> 01:19:30.554
It's epsilon ijk xi xj pk.

01:19:35.110 --> 01:19:41.100
Well, this is 0 because these
two x's are operators but they

01:19:41.100 --> 01:19:42.130
commute.

01:19:42.130 --> 01:19:46.180
Therefore this object is
symmetrical in i and j.

01:19:46.180 --> 01:19:48.070
This is antisymmetric.

01:19:48.070 --> 01:19:49.430
This is 0.

01:19:49.430 --> 01:19:53.540
So r dot L is actually 0.

01:19:56.730 --> 01:20:02.660
How about p dot L.
Well, there's two ways

01:20:02.660 --> 01:20:05.470
of doing that, one that
looks pretty obvious,

01:20:05.470 --> 01:20:07.700
one that looks a little harder.

01:20:07.700 --> 01:20:09.850
Let's do the one that
looks a little harder.

01:20:09.850 --> 01:20:21.400
This would be pi
epsilon ijk xj pk.

01:20:27.330 --> 01:20:30.910
So here is the temptation.

01:20:30.910 --> 01:20:32.180
Must be 0.

01:20:32.180 --> 01:20:34.840
Because there is a pi pk.

01:20:34.840 --> 01:20:38.680
Symmetric in i and k.

01:20:38.680 --> 01:20:41.175
And here's antisymmetric
in i and k.

01:20:41.175 --> 01:20:44.150
But it's this wrong.

01:20:44.150 --> 01:20:46.030
These are not
obviously symmetric

01:20:46.030 --> 01:20:48.310
unless you can move them across.

01:20:48.310 --> 01:20:52.710
And there's an x in the
middle laughing at you

01:20:52.710 --> 01:20:55.690
and saying, beware.

01:20:55.690 --> 01:20:56.820
This could go wrong.

01:20:59.630 --> 01:21:02.890
So you have to be a
little more careful.

01:21:02.890 --> 01:21:05.880
So let's be careful.

01:21:05.880 --> 01:21:16.490
ijk and you put pi xj
pk, all our operators.

01:21:16.490 --> 01:21:23.050
But pi with xj the commutator
would be a delta ij and that

01:21:23.050 --> 01:21:23.710
vanishes.

01:21:23.710 --> 01:21:31.240
So this p actually can be moved
across the x and therefore show

01:21:31.240 --> 01:21:37.240
that the p is on the other side.

01:21:37.240 --> 01:21:39.350
Because the epsilon is there.

01:21:39.350 --> 01:21:40.840
So it's a lucky thing.

01:21:40.840 --> 01:21:48.490
So pi xj pk is not
symmetrical in i and k.

01:21:48.490 --> 01:21:51.240
But if there's an epsilon,
you're in better shape.

01:21:51.240 --> 01:22:00.260
So here the p can be
moved. ijk xj pi pk.

01:22:00.260 --> 01:22:04.930
And now nobody can stop you
from saying this is symmetric.

01:22:04.930 --> 01:22:08.790
They're next to each other, they
can be moved across each other.

01:22:08.790 --> 01:22:11.422
It's really
symmetric in i and k.

01:22:11.422 --> 01:22:15.370
And therefore i and k
antisymmetric, this is 0.

01:22:15.370 --> 01:22:19.790
p dot L is equal to 0 as well.

01:22:19.790 --> 01:22:22.130
So this was a
little bit hard way.

01:22:22.130 --> 01:22:28.970
If you had to used that L is
actually equal to p cross r,

01:22:28.970 --> 01:22:32.480
then the p would have been next
to the p from the beginning.

01:22:32.480 --> 01:22:34.490
And you would have
saved a little time.

01:22:34.490 --> 01:22:36.780
The same time that it
took you to realize

01:22:36.780 --> 01:22:41.110
that this equality is true.

01:22:41.110 --> 01:22:45.380
So those are true equalities.

01:22:45.380 --> 01:22:47.160
p dot L is 0.

01:22:47.160 --> 01:22:51.320
And it's also equal to L dot p.

01:22:51.320 --> 01:22:54.400
It's not obvious
that L and p commute.

01:22:54.400 --> 01:22:58.930
But in this case L dot p is 0.

01:22:58.930 --> 01:23:02.292
If you use this formula
for L, it's obvious.

01:23:02.292 --> 01:23:03.940
r dot L is 0.

01:23:03.940 --> 01:23:07.650
It's also equal to L dot r.

01:23:07.650 --> 01:23:09.440
Doesn't make a difference.

01:23:09.440 --> 01:23:11.890
It's also true as well.

01:23:11.890 --> 01:23:17.230
